>> A2: Briefly describe how you implemented argument parsing.  How do
>> you arrange for the elements of argv[] to be in the right order?
>> How do you avoid overflowing the stack page?

Argument passing is implmented through stack. When the executable file 
is successfully loaded, start_process() calls setup_args that parses the 
command line arguments and sets up the args in the stack.

Inside start_process(), we use strtok_r on the "file_name" variable 
that is passed to start_process to get the args. We follow the 80x86 
calling convention argument passing style. 

Once all the relevant info is pushed to the stack, we check for stack overflow. 
We do this by checking if the esp pointer is still within valid bounds.
For this project, esp must be between PHYS_BASE and PHYS_BASE + PGSIZE.

---- RATIONALE ----

>> A3: Why does Pintos implement strtok_r() but not strtok()?

Pintos implements strtok_r() instead of strtok() to ensure thread safety. 
Unlike strtok(), which uses a static buffer to track token positions, 
strtok_r() takes an extra argument to store this state. This prevents issues 
where a context switch between threads could cause one thread to alter the 
state being used by another, leading to unexpected behavior. With strtok_r(), 
each thread maintains its own tokenization state, ensuring safe and predictable 
operation in a multi-threaded environment.

