>> B4: Suppose a system call causes a full page (4,096 bytes) of data
>> to be copied from user space into the kernel.  What is the least
>> and the greatest possible number of inspections of the page table
>> (e.g. calls to pagedir_get_page()) that might result?  What about
>> for a system call that only copies 2 bytes of data?  Is there room
>> for improvement in these numbers, and how much?

For each system call, we validate the pointers by validating the start address
and the last address by validating that the pointer is not NULL, and that the
start address is a user address and its mapped virtual memory, and that the 
last address is a user address and if its in a different page, we also check
that its mapped to virtual memory. 

Except that for system calls that passes a file name without the length, we 
cant find the last address easily so we have to check the address for each
character in the filename. As in, we check that the pointer is not null and 
that the start address is a user address and its mapped virtual memory like 
before, but then we go over the addresses of the remaining characters one by 
one and check that they're user addresses and if we cross a page boundary we 
check that the address is mapped virtual memorty (we do that for 14 characters
as the max number of characters in a file name is 14). That means that we only
check the page table for the start address, and for the first address in a new
page if we cross a page boundary.

Therefore for the full page (4,096 bytes) case:
a) Least number of inspections is 1, if the whole data is within one page 
exactly (we dont cross a page boundary), then we'll only inspect the page table
for the start address and not the last address.

b) Greatest number of inspections is 2, if the data crosses a page boundary at
some point, meaning that it spans across 2 pages, we'll inspect the page table
for the start address AND the last address.

For the 2 bytes case we get the same answers:
a) Least number of inspections is 1, if both bytes are within one page (we dont 
cross a page boundary), then we'll only inspect the page table for the start 
address and not the last address.

b) Greatest number of inspections is 2, if the 2 bytes overlap a page boundary
then we'll inspect the page table
for the first byte's address AND the second byte's address.

We can improve this by making sure that the data is always copied into a single
page, so that we only need to inspect the page table once.

>> B5: Briefly describe your implementation of the "wait" system call
>> and how it interacts with process termination.

The wait system call is handled by the wait system handler. The wait system 
handler in turn calls process_wait(). process_wait() loops over the children 
processes and find the child struct of the child thread that the current thread 
needs to wait on. 
It then calls sema_down on "exit_sema" which is a semaphore member in the 
childs struct and which is set to 1 and sema_down is called on it when 
thread_create is called for the child process. This ensures the current thread 
waits on the child thread until sema_up is called on "exit_sema" of the child 
thread. 

Inside process_exit() is when the child thread sema ups the "exit_sema". 
Meaning that the parent thread won't be able to continue running until the
child its waiting on exits. The parent thread accesses the childs exit status 
by reading the exit_status member of the child struct. 

>> B6: Any access to user program memory at a user-specified address
>> can fail due to a bad pointer value.  Such accesses must cause the
>> process to be terminated.  System calls are fraught with such
>> accesses, e.g. a "write" system call requires reading the system
>> call number from the user stack, then each of the call's three
>> arguments, then an arbitrary amount of user memory, and any of
>> these can fail at any point.  This poses a design and
>> error-handling problem: how do you best avoid obscuring the primary
>> function of code in a morass of error-handling?  Furthermore, when
>> an error is detected, how do you ensure that all temporarily
>> allocated resources (locks, buffers, etc.) are freed?  In a few
>> paragraphs, describe the strategy or strategies you adopted for
>> managing these issues.  Give an example.

Before executing a system call handler, we verify that the pointers passed by 
the user are valid meaning the lock to perform file-related system won't be 
acquired if the user passes a bad pointer value.
Furthermore, the resources allocated like the files opened, pcb struct, 
child_thread_info struct are all freed at the thread_exit call of either the
process itself or its parent. More specifically, the files are closed and the 
pcb struct is freed on the thread_exit call of the process itself, and its 
child_thread_info struct is freed when its parent exits.
Since we call thread_exit () when we validate a bad pointer value, we ensure 
that files and pcb struct are closed/freed even if the user passes a bad 
pointer value

---- SYNCHRONIZATION ----

>> B7: The "exec" system call returns -1 if loading the new executable
>> fails, so it cannot return before the new executable has completed
>> loading.  How does your code ensure this?  How is the load
>> success/failure status passed back to the thread that calls "exec"?

When the exec system call is called, the exec handler calls process_execute()
on the new file. When the new thread for the exec process is created, its added
as a child thread of the current running thread. The child thread struct
contains a "load_sema" sempahore which is initalized to one and it calls 
sema_down on when its created. Back in exec handler, the current running thread 
calls sema_down on "child->load_sema" which forces the current running thread 
to wait until the child thread calls sema_up on its "load_sema".
The child thread calls sema_up on its load_sema once the file has been loaded
in start_process and sets its loaded member to the load success/failure status. 
This is how we make sure that the current thread does not return until the exec 
has finished loading.

Once the current thread can continue running after sema_down it retrieves the 
load success/failure status by reading the loaded boolean member of the childs 
threads' struct. and returns -1 if its failure, and the childs tid if its 
successful.

>> B8: Consider parent process P with child process C.  How do you
>> ensure proper synchronization and avoid race conditions when P
>> calls wait(C) before C exits?  After C exits?  How do you ensure
>> that all resources are freed in each case?  How about when P
>> terminates without waiting, before C exits?  After C exits?  Are
>> there any special cases?

We're using the semaphore exit_sema which is a field in the child_thread_info 
struct. For process P to create a child process C, process_execute gets called
which calls thread_create, inside thread_create, we set the C's parent to P,
add C to P's list of children and call sema_down on exit_sema. After that
process_execute returns with C's tid for P to be able to wait on it.

If P calls wait(C) before C exits:
wait calls process_wait which finds the child_thread_info struct associated
with C and call sema_down on exit_sema. Since sema_up hasn't been called yet
on it, process_wait will get stuck on the sema_down call till sema_up is called.
When C exits, thread_exit will be called which will call process_exit, there we
call close_files to closes all the files in the fd_table of C as well as C's
executable and free_child_threads which free all the child_thread_info structs
associated with C's child threads if there's any, we'll then free C's pcb as 
well as the page directory and set the exit status. In this function, sema_up 
is called on exit_sema therefore P can continue running now in process_wait 
where it will remove C from the children list and free the child_thread_info 
struct associated with C and return with the exit status of C. 
This way all files opened by C as well as the pcb and child_thread_info structs 
associated with it are closed/freed by the time C exits and P finished waiting. 
Synchronization is achieved such that P doesnt continue running until C exits.

If P calls wait(C) after C exits:
When C exits, thread_exit will be called which will call process_exit, there we
call close_files to closes all the files in the fd_table of C as well as C's
executable and free_child_threads which free all the child_thread_info structs
associated with C's child threads if there's any, we'll then free C's pcb as
well as the page directory and set the exit status. In this function, sema_up is 
called on exit_sema therefore sema_down can be called on exit_sema and not wait.
When wait starts running it calls process_wait which finds the child_thread_info 
struct associated with C and call sema_down on exit_sema, and will continue 
running where it will remove C from the children list and free the 
child_thread_info struct associated with C and return with the exit status of C. 
This way all files opened by C as well as the pcb and child_thread_info structs 
associated with it are closed/freed by the time C exits and P finished waiting. 
Synchronization is achieved such that P doesnt continue running until C exits.

If P terminates without waiting, before C exits:
When P terminates without waiting, P will call thread_exit will be called which 
will call process_exit, there we call close_files to closes all the files in the
fd_table of P as well as P's executable and free_child_threads which frees all 
the child_thread_info structs associated with P's child threads if there's any, 
we'll then free P's pcb as well as the page directory and set the exit status.
After that C exits and it will go through the same process and closes all the 
files in the fd_table of C as well as C's executable and free all the 
child_thread_info structs associated with C's child threads if there's any, 
we'll then free C's pcb as well as the page directory and set the exit status
Therefore C still handled closing its files and freeing its pcb struct and P
still handled freeing the child_thread_info struct associated with C since it
freed all its children's child_thread_info structs.
Synchronization is not needed since P doesnt wait on C

If P terminates without waiting, after C exits:
The same happens except that C exits first so it closes its files and frees its
pcb struct first and then P exits and frees the child_thread_info struct for C.
We still freed all the resources we needed to free.
Synchronization is also not needed since P doesnt wait on C

